The idea of this problem is pretty simple, we wish to count the number of Valleys and Hills in the array.
The solution used in this problem is focused on simplicity and being easy to understand.
This is O(n) time complexity, and O(n) memory complexity.

**Strategy:**

So, to find if a number is a hill or a valley, we need to see if the neighboring values that aren't the same are both an increase or decrease relative to this number.

Step 1:

Make sure that there are no neighboring nodes of the same values, so turning something like ``[6,7,7,7,8,8,9,2] -> [6,7,8,9,2]``.

Step 2:

Loop through the array starting at the 2nd index and up to the 2nd last index, and increase the return value if a nodes neighbors are both greater than or less than the node.

**Solution:**

**C++**

```
int countHillValley(vector<int>& ns) {
    //Step 1
    std::vector<int> nums;
    int l = ns[0];
    nums.push_back(l);
    for (int n : ns) {
        if (n != l) {
            nums.push_back(n);
            l = n;
        }
    }

    //Step 2.
    int ret = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i < nums.size() - 1; i++) {
        if (nums[i-1] < nums[i] == nums[i+1] < nums[i]) ret++;
    }
    return ret;
}
```

