Basic approach: 
Pointers:
Initially, 'prev' will point to 0th index
'current' will point to first index, 
'next' will point to second index,
'count' to count hills & valleys

Loop till your 'next' reached last index.

* (EQUAL NEIGHBOURS) check if your values in current is same as next, if yes , move 'current' and 'next' to +1 index and skip the iteration using continue;
* (NON EQUAL NEIGHBOURS-VALLEY) If your current value is less than both 'prev' and 'next', increase your count+1
* (NON EQUAL NEIGHBOURS-HILL) If your current value is greater than both 'prev' and 'next', increase your count+1
* Finally, make 'prev' index to current, 'current' index to next, and increase next+1; 

NOTE: You can reduce your space complexity by using i+1 instead of defining 'next', but then you have to make amendments to your algorithm. 

```
class Solution {
    public int countHillValley(int[] nums) {
        int count=0;
        int prev=0;
        int next=2;
        int current=1;
        while(next<nums.length)
        {
            if(nums[current]==nums[next])
            {  
             current+=1;next+=1;
             continue;
            }

            else
            {    
            if(nums[prev]>nums[current] && nums[next]>nums[current])
            {   
                count++;

            }
            else if(nums[prev]<nums[curent] && nums[next]<nums[current])
            {   
                count++; 
             }
            }
            prev=current;current=next;next++;


        }
        return(count);

    }
}
```

