solutions.content:
#### Bitmask Tracing
Here, we build a grid to place guards and walls, and trace guarded cells. 

One way to avoid TLE is to place all guards first (and walls, of course), and then trace from each guard in four directions until you hit an edge, a wall, or another guard.

Here, however, we track the direction for each cell using a bitmask. We stop when we hit a cell that was already traced in the same direction. That way, we do not have to place all guards first.

**C++**
```cpp
int dir[5] = {0, 1, 0, -1, 0};
int countUnguarded(int m, int n, vector<vector<int>>& guards, vector<vector<int>>& walls) {
    int not_guarded = m * n - walls.size();
    vector<vector<int>> g(m, vector<int>(n));
    for (const auto &wall : walls)
        g[wall[0]][wall[1]] = 15;
    for (const auto &gd : guards)
        for (int d = 0; d < 4; ++d)
            for (int i = gd[0], j = gd[1]; min(i, j) >= 0 && i < m && j < n && (g[i][j] & (1 << d)) == 0; ) {
                not_guarded -= g[i][j] == 0;
                g[i][j] += (1 << d);
                i += dir[d];
                j += dir[d + 1];
            }
    return not_guarded;
}
```
#### Binary Search
This solution is efficient for a large grid with a few guards and walls.

For this solution, we track the position of guards and walls in `rows` and `cols` arrays, sorted. Instead of using a grid to trace guarded cells, we use binary search to find out the closest guard or wall in all four directions.

When there is a wall in all four directions (or nothing), the cell is not guarded. 

**C++**
```cpp
int countUnguarded(int m, int n, vector<vector<int>>& guards, vector<vector<int>>& walls) {
    vector<vector<pair<int, int>>> rows(m, vector<pair<int, int>>{{-1, 1}, {n, 1}}), cols(n, vector<pair<int, int>>{{-1, 1}, {m, 1}});
    for (auto &g : guards) {
        rows[g[0]].push_back({g[1], 0});
        cols[g[1]].push_back({g[0], 0});
    }
    for (auto &w : walls) {
        rows[w[0]].push_back({w[1], 1});
        cols[w[1]].push_back({w[0], 1});
    }
    for (auto &r : rows)
        sort(begin(r), end(r));
    for (auto &c : cols)
        sort(begin(c), end(c));
    int res = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
            auto it_r = lower_bound(begin(rows[i]), end(rows[i]), pair<int, int>{j, 0});
            auto it_c = lower_bound(begin(cols[j]), end(cols[j]), pair<int, int>{i, 0});
            if (it_r->first == j && it_c->first == i)
                continue;
            if (it_r->second == 0 || it_c->second == 0 || prev(it_r)->second == 0 || prev(it_c)->second == 0)
                continue;         
            ++res;
        }
    }
    return res;
}
```

