solutions.content:
### DFS Solution ~ O(M*N)
- This is a basic DFS question, but with few extra condition checks.
- Initially we mark the existence of 
	- **`walls`** as **`2`** 
	- **`guards`** as **`3`**
	- **`vison of guards`** as **`1`**.
- Here we don't require `visited` array, since we can do it using the `walls` and other `guards` in adjacent cell. 
- Keep track of the changes using the `occupied` count and our answer would be the remaining  count.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f9ea4a0a-c03b-4c39-b305-30e97d8aa513_1651334847.8484206.png)

```cpp
int countUnguarded(int m, int n, vector<vector<int>>& guards, vector<vector<int>>& walls) {
    int dir[][2] = {{1,0},{0,1},{-1,0},{0,-1}};

	vector<vector<int>> grid(m, vector<int>(n, 0));
    int occupied = walls.size() + guards.size();

    for(auto& w: walls)
        grid[w[0]][w[1]] = 2;

    for(auto& g: guards)
        grid[g[0]][g[1]] = 3;

	// DFS from each guards position
    for(auto& g: guards){
        int x = g[0], y = g[1];

        for(int k=0; k<4; k++){
            int dx = x, dy = y;
            while(true){
                dx += dir[k][0];   
                dy += dir[k][1];

				// break if you see a wall, or if another guard is standing infront of you. ("not vision")
                if(min(dx, dy) < 0 || dx == m || dy == n || grid[dx][dy] == 2 || grid[dx][dy] == 3)
                    break;

				// if two guards can vision the same cell (1,0) or (1, 3) in example, dont occupy++
                if(grid[dx][dy] != 1){
                    grid[dx][dy] = 1;
                    occupied++;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return m*n - occupied;
}
```

