class Solution {
	int[] dRow = new int[]{-1, 0, 1, 0};
	int[] dCol = new int[]{0, 1, 0, -1};

	public int countUnguarded(int m, int n, int[][] guards, int[][] walls) {        
		int[][] grid = new int[m][n];

		for(int[] loc : guards) {
			grid[loc[0]][loc[1]] = 1;
		}

		for(int[] loc : walls) {
			grid[loc[0]][loc[1]] = 2;
		}

		boolean[][][] isVisited = new boolean[m][n][4];

		for(int i=0; i<m; i++) {
			for(int j=0; j<n; j++) {
				if(grid[i][j] == 1) {
					for(int k=0; k<4; k++) {
						if(!isVisited[i][j][k]) {
							isVisited[i][j][k] = true;
							helper(i, j, k, grid, isVisited);
						}
					}
				}
			}
		}

		int ans = 0;
		for(int i=0; i<m; i++) {
			for(int j=0; j<n; j++) {
				if(grid[i][j] == 0) ans++;
			}
		}

		return ans;

	}

	public void helper(int row, int col, int dir, int[][] grid, boolean[][][] isVisited) {
		int nRow = row + dRow[dir];
		int nCol = col + dCol[dir];

		if(nRow < 0 || nRow >= grid.length || nCol < 0 || nCol >= grid[0].length || isVisited[nRow][nCol][dir] || grid[nRow][nCol] == 2 || grid[nRow][nCol] == 1) return;

		grid[nRow][nCol] = 3;
		isVisited[nRow][nCol][dir] = true;
		helper(nRow, nCol, dir, grid, isVisited);
	}
}

The below is based on @votrubac solution [here](https://leetcode.com/problems/count-unguarded-cells-in-the-grid/discuss/2001912/Bitmask-Tracing-vs.-Binary-Search), though instead of doing a bitmask we opt for a simpler scheme just count if we are about to walk through a path already traveled by another guard.

 This does a few nice things for speed and clarity relative to the original post, though could probably be improved

1. Removes iterating over the guards original position each time in the innermost loop
2. Instead of using a bit mask the program checks if another guard has already traveled down that particular path or if we hit a wall
3. Moves the iterating of i and j out of the loop body and into the loop decleration 
4. Uses a constexpr array for the directions
5. Adds a matrix class for the grid

I couldn't think of a counter example that makes the below wrong but would be very happy if someone could fine one!

Just to clarify on the value 2 in the below. Imagine we have a guard coming from the top and the right whose paths intersect. Once we put a value of 2 at where their paths intersect, if a guard comes from the right or bottom then once they see 2 other guards have already gone down that path they know there is no need to travel any further. Similarly walls have a value of 2 since we want the guard to stop at that point.

```cpp
// So that our grid is one 
// big chunk of memory instead of a vector of vectors
struct Matrix {
  int* arr;
  int rows;
  int cols;
  Matrix(const int n, const int m) noexcept
      : rows(n), cols(m), arr(static_cast<int*>(calloc(n * m, sizeof(int)))) {}
  inline int& operator()(int i, int j) noexcept { return arr[i * cols + j]; }
};

class Solution {
 public:
  using array_2i = std::array<int, 2>;
  // up, right, down, left
  static constexpr std::array<array_2i, 4> directions{array_2i{0, 1}, 
                                                      array_2i{1, 0},
                                                      array_2i{0, -1},
                                                      array_2i{-1, 0}};
  int countUnguarded(int m, int n, vector<vector<int>>& guards,
                     vector<vector<int>>& walls) {
    int not_guarded = m * n - walls.size() - guards.size();
    Matrix grid(m, n);
    /*
     * These get set to 2 just to indicate we've traveled through them
     * at least once. At that point we intersect with another 
     *  guard so no need to keep going.
     * NOTE: That's my intuition on the above, I think it is correct?
     */  
    for (auto&& wall : walls) {
      grid(wall[0], wall[1]) = 2;
    }
    for (auto&& guard : guards) {
      grid(guard[0], guard[1]) = 2;
    }
    for (auto&& guard : guards) {
      for (auto&& path_direction : directions) {
        /**
         * For each guard and direction, travel until we hit:
         * 1. An edge (either negative values or positive oob)
         * 2. We come across another guards path
         */
        for (int i = guard[0] + path_direction[0],
                 j = guard[1] + path_direction[1];
              min(i, j) >= 0 && i < m && j < n && grid(i, j) < 2;
              i += path_direction[0],
              j += path_direction[1]) {
          if (grid(i, j) == 0) {
            --not_guarded;
            grid(i, j) += 1;
          }
        }
      }
    }
    return not_guarded;
  }
};
```

Thanks for reading! Please like this post if you use the code and feel free to comment with any improvements or questions! One thing I didn't try but could be faster it to forgo using a grid and instead have an unordered map with a cheap hash function to keep track of where the guards have traveled.

